data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core's Cosmos DB provider, the **sync-over-async opt-in is removed**. The temporary compatibility switch that allowed synchronous LINQ execution (introduced when sync operations were first blocked by default) is no longer available.

**All four of your methods will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime:**

| Method | Blocking call | Async replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `GetAll()` | `ToList()` | `ToListAsync()` |
| `GetById()` | `First()` | `FirstAsync()` |
| `GetCount()` | `Count()` | `CountAsync()` |
| `Save()` | `SaveChanges()` | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

### The fix — convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- The Cosmos SDK is inherently async-only; sync support was always a shim calling `.Result`/`.Wait()` internally, risking deadlocks.
- `Add()` is an in-memory operation and stays synchronous — only the database-hitting calls need `await`.
- This is an **async-all-the-way** change: callers up the chain (controllers, handlers) must also become `async Task<>`.
